## Open Decisions
- Production DB: Postgres first; OpenSearch/vector/graph later.
- Queue: start embedded for tests; production likely Redis/NATS/Postgres advisory queue.
- Browser pool: disabled by default until RSS/static adapters are stable.
- Darknet fetchers: metadata-only until legal/ethics review signs off source classes.

## Immediate Agent Assignments
- Agent 03: move clear-web collection from fixture-level correctness toward production workload readiness. Add crawl-state outputs for ETag, Last-Modified, final URL, redirect chain, status class, fetch duration, parser version, parser warnings, and adapter failure category. Wire these signals so Agent 01 health/scoring and Agent 02 frontier can consume them. Add tests for redirects, 304, 429 Retry-After, canonical duplicate URLs, malformed feeds, and large page caps using `CollectionTask.maxBytes`.
- Agent 09: keep `/v1` API stable while adding OpenAPI/schema generation plan. Do not break the current 43 passing tests.
- Agent 10: review `src/ops/*` against 96 GB target and 160 GB ceiling; add tests around memory/concurrency budget calculations.
- All agents Task C direction: move from scaffold correctness to production source activation. Prioritize end-to-end `APT29` and actor-query workflows: source selection, collection planning, capture provenance, extraction, run status, result ranking, API contracts, and operational safety. Avoid cosmetic UI/marketing work. Any adapter that touches darknet, Telegram, forums, or leak-site material must keep metadata-only controls and approval gates intact.
- All agents Task D direction: do not mark ready after small patches. Each agent now owns a production program with docs, contracts, fixtures, tests, integration coordination, and clear exit criteria. The objective is enterprise operational usefulness: approved sources, transparent scheduling, real collection, immutable provenance, deterministic extraction, graph-backed results, API integration, and bounded operations.
- All agents Task E direction: close the gap between the deployed live-search fallback and scraper-native production behavior. Arbitrary actor queries must return immediate partial evidence, start/reuse a run, expose progress/polling, promote discovery evidence into captures/extractions/graph relationships, and surface source activation gaps without unsafe collection.
- All agents Task F direction: finish the real production mechanics behind live search: run reuse, public traffic backpressure, cursor/delta polling, promotion from discovery to captures/extractions/graph, safe public-channel/darknet metadata deltas, API compatibility for removing the outer fallback, and deploy-time proof checks for `/ti?q=...`.
- Task G direction for reassigned agents: convert live-search subsystems from technically functional into enterprise-operable: source approval bridges, persistent evidence cutover, honest confidence/caveat semantics, analyst graph review states, and readiness gates for removing the temporary outer Hanasand fallback.
- Task H direction for reassigned agents: prepare for production promotion of scraper-native search: durable scheduler/storage/graph/API contracts, source-pack compliance, backup/restore drills, actor-profile drift controls, public soak tests, rollback criteria, and proof commands.
- Task I direction for all agents: make scraper-native live search production-operable end to end. Arbitrary actor queries should move from live discovery to canonical captures, extraction, graph deltas, source activation recommendations, API cursor polling, and soak-tested deployment gates while preserving strict metadata-only controls for restricted sources.
- Task J direction for reassigned agents: move from component readiness into production reconciliation and auditability. Operators need to see drift, skipped work, blocked sources, stale evidence, weak extraction, graph export blockers, deployment drift, and concrete safe repair plans without triggering unsafe collection.
- Task K direction for reassigned agents: rehearse scraper-native search cutover end to end. Produce compact readiness reports, proof helpers, blockers, rollback paths, and promotion-gate fields so the main agent can decide when the outer fallback can be removed safely.
- Task L direction for reassigned agents: convert cutover findings into safe dry-run apply plans. No production mutation yet: each plan must state prerequisites, expected diff/effect, rollback, policy impact, and whether the action is automation-safe, human-approval-required, blocked, or rollback-only.
- Task M direction for reassigned agents: freeze API-facing contracts for apply plans, replay proof, quality gates, graph review, and promotion packets so Agent 09 can wire `/v1/intel/search` and the outer API can cut over without reading internal implementation details.
- Task N direction for reassigned agents: wire frozen contracts into route handlers, CLI proof paths, and contract tests. Keep all new endpoints dry-run and non-mutating unless an explicit future apply operation is approved.
- Task O direction for reassigned agents: prove mounted endpoints and CLI gates work through the actual Bun API/server and Inspur command paths, not just helper-level unit tests. Outputs must stay compact, dry-run, and safe.
- Task P direction for reassigned agents: move from route proof to production data-path cutover. The standard is usable CTI: arbitrary actor queries should schedule approved collection, promote evidence safely, fuse profile results with provenance, expose graph/STIX semantics, and survive 24h soak without unsafe collection or resource drift.
- Task Q direction: runtime integration and cutover closure. Every workstream must prove its piece through actual route contracts, actor-query fixtures, provenance, safety gates, and operational proof. Agent 03 must resolve clear-web discovery-to-capture status; Agent 09 must publish `Status: api_readiness_report` at the top of its file before claiming readiness.
- Task R direction: tighten production-readiness gates around measurable SLOs, claim-level provenance, public compatibility, and soak decisions. Agent 03 remains a clear-web status blocker. Agent 09 is no longer missing the report, but remains API-cutover blocked until scraper-native top-level compatibility fields and correct POST public proof are green.
- Task S direction: move completed workstreams from readiness reports into production operating contracts. The shared target is real CTI operations: source portfolio onboarding, worker loop economics, public-channel runtime, restricted metadata governance, evidence ledger, answer quality, graph/STIX readiness, API cutover proof, and blocker-aware soak/release decisions. Agent 03 and Agent 09 remain explicit blockers until their top reports are corrected with current proof.
- Task T direction: push from operating contracts toward runtime release rehearsal. Key goals are source activation batches, route-visible scheduler execution, public-channel-to-answer readiness, restricted metadata kill-switch proof, claim-ledger APIs, multi-source answer fusion, graph export gates, stable scraper-native API cutover semantics, and production release proof. Agent 03 remains the only stale-status blocker.
- Task U direction: move runtime release contracts into measurable SLAs and deployment gates. Every unblocked workstream should expose compact SLA state, safe dry-run remediation, public answer/API impact, and release-packet proof. Agent 03 stale status remains a blocker until corrected with required proof.
- Task V direction: enforce the SLA and release-gate contracts. Workstreams must emit compact holds/warnings, dry-run repair packets, public API impact, and promotion/rollback proof. Agent 03 stale clear-web status is still a blocker.
- Task W direction: move enforcement into production integration closure. Completed lanes now own safe source activation waves, concrete worker queue cutover models, public-channel source packs, restricted metadata audit replay, analyst-grade answer fusion, graph/STIX/TAXII readiness, API contract freeze, and release-train soak orchestration. Agent 06 continues Task V evidence promotion holds; Agent 03 remains the only stale clear-web blocker.
- Task X direction: move from integration closure into release-candidate certification. Workstreams must produce dry-run execution/canary/certification packets, route-visible contracts, no-leak proof, public API compatibility, and release-gate evidence for production rollout. Agent 03 remains fail-closed until clear-web discovery-to-capture proof is current.
- Task Y direction: move selected completed lanes into canary execution proof. Focus on scheduler adapter telemetry, public-channel evidence canary, restricted kill-switch drills, live public-answer polling semantics, and release rollback proof. Active Task X lanes continue uninterrupted; Agent 03 remains fail-closed.
- Task Z direction: final release-candidate proof. All unblocked lanes must produce operator-grade dry-run promotion/canary/certification packets with route-visible contracts, no-leak proof, rollback paths, public `/ti` compatibility, and Agent 10 RC board integration. Agent 03 stale clear-web status remains fail-closed for full production promotion.
